e the need for training, the unmanageable amount of paperwork in large organizations, difficulty in ranking packages, time constraints for top-level management, complexity and time consumption, inability to react to changes during the year, and potential prioritization of short-term goals over long-term objectives.\"", "\"WHEN ZBB IS APPROPRIATE\":\"ZBB is most appropriate in organizations with a high portion of discretionary costs, such as research and development, training, and advertising. It enables reassessment of spending on discretionary items.\"", "\"USE OF ZBB IN THE PUBLIC SECTOR\":\"ZBB is more prevalent in public sector bodies due to its transparency in showing budgets based on activities rather than line items, and its usefulness in ranking decision packages to allocate limited resources effectively.\"", "\"ZBB\":Zero-Based Budgeting (ZBB) is a budgeting method where all expenses must be justified for each new period, starting from a 'zero base.' Every function within an organization is analyzed for its needs and costs.", "\"WEEKLY BUDGETED COSTS\":\"Weekly budgeted costs include the total direct costs and total indirect costs. Direct costs are calculated based on materials and direct labor, while indirect costs include machine set-ups, purchase orders, and storage costs. The total costs are the sum of direct and indirect costs.\"", "\"ADVANTAGES OF ABB\":\"Advantages of Activity-Based Budgeting (ABB) include focusing management attention on controllable activities, providing opportunities for cost reductions, and identifying non-value adding activities that can be eliminated.\"", "\"DISADVANTAGES OF ABB\":\"Disadvantages of Activity-Based Budgeting (ABB) include its complexity and expense to implement, especially if direct costs are more significant than indirect costs and the product range is narrow. ABB may also provide misleading information if many fixed costs do not vary with changes in the volume of drivers in the short run.\"", "\"APPROPRIATENESS OF ABB\":\"Activity-Based Budgeting (ABB) is most appropriate in large companies with high overheads, many different activities (drivers) to which the overheads relate, and many products with differing production times and methods.\"", "\"FEEDBACK CONTROL\":\"Feedback control is a system in which outputs are monitored against a predetermined standard, and action is taken to remedy any deviations. A budgetary control system is an example of a feedback control system.\"", "\"CLOSED-LOOP SYSTEM\":\"A closed-loop system is any system with feedback, making it reactive rather than proactive. It includes a standard, sensor, comparator, and effector to control actions.\"", "\"OPEN-LOOP SYSTEM\":\"An open-loop system is a system without feedback. Feedback may be absent because it is not produced or not used appropriately.\"", "\"POSITIVE AND NEGATIVE FEEDBACK\":\"Positive feedback means the output has achieved or exceeded the plan, while negative feedback means the output is below the plan. Both types of feedback should be investigated to determine corrective actions or repeat favorable outcomes.\"", "\"FEED-FORWARD CONTROL\":\"Feed-forward control systems compare predicted future results against the desired outcome. If the desired result will not be achieved based on the current prediction, action can be taken now to ensure it is achieved.\"", "\"FORECASTING\":\"A budget is effectively a forecast of what can be achieved. The forecast has to make assumptions about the external environment, including factors like economic performance, competitor actions, employee performance, market prices of inputs, and demand for new products.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}